commentBody:
@Susan

Denali Denali Denali 

He can come find me. I'll be near the Gulf of Mexico.

@Mike 

I don’t want to be THAT commenter, but this is Wordplay, so here goes…wouldn’t “sneezed to meet you” be what the NOSE says to the handkerchief? 

I’ll show myself out now.

@Beth

HONEY_O crossing O_IE confused me. I know almost nothing about Garfield, and I can't see how HONEYDO makes sense.

The puzzle was saturated with names and trivia, in general, but most of it was gettable with crosses.

@Vaer

Thank you. I'm sure I have seen ODIE in these puzzles before, but the name is just so strange I can't remember it, and not being familiar with Garfield means I lack proper context that would help me remember by association with what I know.

I know what a to do list is, obviously, but going from "to do" to simply "do" was too much of a mental leap for me.

@Andrzej

And by the way, you're not the only curmudgeon who was annoyed by this puzzle. For a different take, see Rex Parker's blog. He doesn't usually agree with the always-glowing reviews by the author and commenters on Wordplay. 
<a href="https://rexwordpuzzle.blogspot.com/2025" target="_blank">https://rexwordpuzzle.blogspot.com/2025</a>/

@Times Rita

Thank you for the kind words. I really like this community - but in a way that is one of the reasons I think I should take a break. As I find these puzzles less and less enjoayble, my feelings about them are becoming increasingly negative. I don't want to bring this negativity here and flaunt it in the face of the fine denizens of Crosslandia. The last thing anybody needs is more grief, right? This is why I hid my today's comments deep down within the structure of the board.

I've been under some stress lately, which is probably much more to blame for my perception of NYT grids than they themselves are. Things should get better within a few months, so if I do go, I should be back.

@Megan
I thought this was easier than a Monday -- at least my time was faster then average.
But I did love the puzzle.  Lots of interesting clues for a Monday, and the theme was priceless!

@Phil

I don’t speak Spanish but grew up on looney toons cartoons, including Speedy Gonzales and his catch phrase of “Andale, andale, arriba!”

(And ILK is a good one to file away in the memory bank; it’s common crosswordese)

@Eric Hougland
The place I went to hang out at to drink and dance during that era was nicknamed the Casbah. Needless to say, the place always went a little nuts when that song played. 
London Calling was on my turntable(!) continually back then.

@Jeremy

I remember the TV series “Spenser for Hire,” though I don’t think I ever watched it. I hadn’t known until just now that it was based on a series of novels. 

I don’t know why I thought the comic’s name is Susan. I know better.

@Momerlyn
I’m on my iPad as usual. I think the difference is I’ve re signed up to the full NYT package (news etc).  Your news is so ‘exciting’ over there I need full commentary. 😱

Even though I’m still using the games app it’s completely changed the set up. My comments are now posted through an email format rather than the comments box at the top of the comms section. It looks weird. Took me an age to figure it out.  Even more irritating it means I can’t see the comment I’m responding to (like yours). Just leave things alone guys, it was fine as it was!

@Steve L
@Eric Houghland.
I think that’s what happened to me the last time I had the news app. So irritating. I’ll delete it and see if that helps.

@Helen Wright

I’m glad to hear you’ve got it back to the way you like it. 

It’s annoying when the tech engineers take something that works perfectly fine and mess it up by making some “improvement’ that makes it less useful.

@Barry Ancona

Thanks! 

Another one for the “blunt instrument” category.

@M

Don't listen to them! 
I really want to see you get two ARMS into one sleeve. Should make the Guiness Book of World Sillies....

@Barry Ancona

My husband has a pullover hoodie that he’s been known to put on backwards. 

Perhaps M has similar difficulties dressing themselves.

@M

To out a finer point on it, the clue refers to “*A* sleeve” not “sleeve*S*”. 

So, arms go in sleeves but an arm goes in a sleeve.

@Byron

No, but I do have a photo of the last time he did it.

Of course, in my haste to get the picture, I blocked part of the lens with my thumb.

@jennie Thank you! That was my confusion, didn't realize "contents" can be plural/singular interchangeably since I never speak that way.

@Grant I get your point, but frankly, knowing there is coffee inside your cup I wouldn't think to say "the contents of your cup," I'd just say "the content of your cup is coffee." Now I know that either works.

@Everyone else The snooty comments are not necessary, it was a simple, innocent question asked in order to learn for next time. Sorry that my ignorance is too much for all of you.

@Marshall Walthew

All y'all are LATE.  Down here in the Southern states we have been sneezing, sniffling, coughing, hacking, blowing, and weeping for more than 6 weeks, thanks to an early Pollen Season (which is predicted to last longer than usual.)  All of our cars are yellow.  Puddles are rimmed with decorative yellow collars; ditto creeks and lakes. If you catch it at the right moment, you can see a pine tree emit an explosion of pollen--timing the release for maximum results.  
Kleenex sales are through the roof...

@Bruce

Loblolly pines are the Mississippi state tree.  The  "explosions" are interesting to witness, but of course there are many, many more sources of pollen.  

May not have mentioned, but I was born in GA and spent some Summer times with cousins in south GA (Bainbridge) where my uncle was lead researcher at the International Paper experimental forest.  Other than 5 yrs of HS, I haven't lived in Atlanta for any length of time, but it's still part of my "origin story."  And the pine trees on the four acres where my folks built their house are not forgotten...

@Hardroch

Yeah, exactly that.

Tapping a tree like that with a piece of heavy equipment, by the way, can easily kill it. You wouldn't think so, but it's true.

@Hardroch

That is astonishing!!!

I've never seen or even heard of this.

@Pete

I stopped caring about my time a while ago and don't always fill in answers lest I miss reading all of the clues, but haven't turned off the clock.

Today was an ideal combination of pleasure and speed. Thanks, Mr. van Geel!

@ad absurdum

You made me laugh. Do you remember the song:
"Idi, Idi, Idi Amin. Most amazing man that there has ever been. He the general, the president, the king of the scene. Idi, Idi, Idi Amin."

@ad absurdum
I've often wondered what Forest Whitaker's initial reaction was when his agent pitched "Last King of Scotland" to him. He couldn't have imagined he'd get an Oscar out of the deal.

(Apart from the nepotism, your post is indeed absurd, but I'm not saying it wasn't funny.)

@Barry Ancona
What in my response did you interpret as a beef? I was simply expanding on why some (a lot?) of us don't know the brand.

And as for needing crosses, see my reply to Andrzej's comment on Rex Parker's review of this one (maybe also chech the review for context).

